  <section class="ems-section">
    <div class="ems-section-label">
      <span class="ems-section-label-num">04</span>
      <span class="ems-section-label-text">Decision Log</span>
      <span class="ems-section-label-line"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="ems-decision-list">

      <div class="ems-decision-card">
        <div class="ems-decision-header">
          <span class="ems-decision-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-title">MVC 5 + Web API 2 for Government Document Lifecycle</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-problem">The EMS handles government-regulated excise documents with complex state machines — documents move through Draft → Internal Approval → Government Approval → Completed. Each transition triggers Crystal Reports generation, SAP XML messaging, and audit logging. Simple CRUD patterns wouldn't suffice.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-chosen"> Chosen — MVC 5 with State Machine Workflow</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">Each document type (CK4C, LACK1, PBCK1, etc.) had a dedicated controller with workflow actions: ApproveDocument, RejectDocument, GovApproveDocument, CompleteDocument. A shared WORKFLOW_STATE table tracked transitions with configurable state machines. Web API 2 provided REST endpoints for the workflow engine.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Workflow Engine / BPMN</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">A dedicated BPMN engine like Camunda or Windows Workflow Foundation would have provided visual process design and monitoring. However, the tight integration with Crystal Reports print triggers, SAP XML outbound, and email notifications per state transition made custom state management more practical and debuggable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-code">
<pre><span class="ems-token-cm">// CK4C document approval with workflow transition</span>
[<span class="ems-token-fn">HttpPost</span>]
<span class="ems-token-kw">public</span> ActionResult <span class="ems-token-fn">GovApproveDocument</span>(<span class="ems-token-kw">string</span> id)
&#123;
    <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> doc = _ck4cBll.<span class="ems-token-fn">GetById</span>(id);
    doc.Status = WorkflowState.GovApproved;

    <span class="ems-token-fn">_workflow</span>.<span class="ems-token-fn">LogTransition</span>(id, WorkflowState.GovApproved, CurrentUser);
    <span class="ems-token-fn">_reporting</span>.<span class="ems-token-fn">GeneratePrintOut</span>(doc);
    <span class="ems-token-fn">_sapMessaging</span>.<span class="ems-token-fn">SendOutbound</span>(doc);

    <span class="ems-token-kw">return</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">RedirectToAction</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"Index"</span>);
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ems-decision-card">
        <div class="ems-decision-header">
          <span class="ems-decision-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-title">Crystal Reports Over Modern Reporting Tools</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-problem">Government excise forms have strict, legally-mandated print layouts with specific fonts, barcode/QR code placement, paper sizes, and watermarks. Each CK/PBCK/LACK form requires exact print reproductions that match the DJBC's official format — deviations could result in regulatory non-compliance.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-chosen"> Chosen — Crystal Reports + iTextSharp</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">44 Crystal Reports (.rpt) files were designed pixel-perfect to match government form specifications. Crystal Reports' precise layout engine handled complex headers, subreports, and conditional sections. iTextSharp supplemented with dynamic PDF generation for digital delivery. QR codes via QRCoder were embedded for government verification.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — JS PDF / SSRS / Power BI</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">Modern alternatives like jsPDF or Power BI couldn't match the pixel-level control needed for legal print forms. SSRS was considered but had limitations with complex subreport nesting and barcode positioning. Crystal Reports, despite its legacy tooling, was the only option that met the strict regulatory requirements.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-code">
<pre><span class="ems-token-cm">// Crystal Reports print-out generation with QR Code</span>
<span class="ems-token-kw">public byte</span>[] <span class="ems-token-fn">GenerateCK4CPrintOut</span>(CK4C document)
&#123;
    <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> report = <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">ReportDocument</span>();
    report.<span class="ems-token-fn">Load</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"~/Reports/CK4C_PrintOut.rpt"</span>);

    <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> qrCode = <span class="ems-token-fn">GenerateQRCode</span>(document.Id);
    report.<span class="ems-token-fn">SetParameterValue</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"QRCodeImage"</span>, qrCode);
    report.<span class="ems-token-fn">SetDataSource</span>(document.Items);

    <span class="ems-token-kw">return</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">ExportToPdf</span>(report);
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ems-decision-card">
        <div class="ems-decision-header">
          <span class="ems-decision-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-title">SAP XML Messaging Over Direct API</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-problem">SAP ByDesign integration required bi-directional data flow — excise document approvals needed to trigger inventory movements (GI, GR, STO) in SAP, while SAP material movements needed to appear in EMS. Direct REST/SOAP calls from the web application risked blocking the UI thread during SAP's potentially slow responses.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-chosen"> Chosen — Async XML Messaging via File Exchange</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">A dedicated XMLReader project parsed inbound SAP files. Outbound messages were generated as XML and placed in network folders for SAP pickup. Quartz.NET scheduler processed the queue asynchronously. This decoupled EMS from SAP availability and provided reliable audit trails via XML_LOGS tables.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Real-time SOAP/REST API</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">SAP ByDesign's native OData/SOAP APIs would have provided real-time integration. However, SAP API rate limits, network latency from the Indonesian data center, and the need for transactional integrity across systems made the file-based approach more robust. The tradeoff was 15-30 minute sync latency.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-code">
<pre><span class="ems-token-cm">// XML outbound message for SAP STO creation</span>
<span class="ems-token-kw">public void</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">SendOutbound</span>(CK4C document)
&#123;
    <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> xml = <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XDocument</span>(
        <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"ExciseDocument"</span>,
            <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XAttribute</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"Type"</span>, <span class="ems-token-str">"CK4C"</span>),
            <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"DocumentId"</span>, document.Id),
            <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"Status"</span>, document.Status),
            <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"Items"</span>, document.Items.<span class="ems-token-fn">Select</span>(i => <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"Item"</span>,
                <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"MaterialId"</span>, i.MaterialId),
                <span class="ems-token-kw">new</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">XElement</span>(<span class="ems-token-str">"Quantity"</span>, i.Quantity))))));

    <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> path = <span class="ems-token-fn">Path</span>.<span class="ems-token-fn">Combine</span>(_config.SapOutboundPath,
        <span class="ems-token-str">$"EMS_CK4C_&#123;document.Id&#125;_&#123;DateTime.Now:yyyyMMddHHmmss&#125;.xml"</span>);
    xml.<span class="ems-token-fn">Save</span>(path);
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ems-decision-card">
        <div class="ems-decision-header">
          <span class="ems-decision-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-title">Active Directory / LDAP Authentication</div>
            <div class="problem">The tobacco industry is heavily regulated — only authorized personnel can access excise documents, approve payments, or submit to government. With hundreds of users across plants, warehouses, and HQ, managing passwords separately from the corporate AD would have been a security and operational risk.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-chosen"> Chosen — LDAP + Role-Based Authorization</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">A custom `[AuthorizeAD]` attribute validated users against Active Directory on every request. Roles (POA, Controller, Viewer, FL Approver, SCCS, Admin, SuperAdmin) were mapped via BROLE_MAP and PAGE tables. Each menu/action was authorized independently using page-level permissions.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-label ems-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — ASP.NET Identity / OAuth</div>
            <div class="ems-decision-col-text">ASP.NET Identity with OAuth would have provided social login and modern token-based auth. However, the corporate environment required strict AD group management, and the government audit trail needed user identity to trace back to the corporate directory. LDAP provided native integration without credential duplication.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ems-decision-code">
<pre><span class="ems-token-cm">// Custom LDAP authorization attribute</span>
[<span class="ems-token-fn">AttributeUsage</span>(AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Method)]
<span class="ems-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">AuthorizeADAttribute</span> : AuthorizeAttribute
&#123;
    <span class="ems-token-kw">protected override bool</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">AuthorizeCore</span>(HttpContextBase httpContext)
    &#123;
        <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> identity = httpContext.User.Identity <span class="ems-token-kw">as</span> WindowsIdentity;
        <span class="ems-token-kw">if</span> (identity == <span class="ems-token-kw">null</span>) <span class="ems-token-kw">return</span> <span class="ems-token-kw">false</span>;

        <span class="ems-token-kw">var</span> user = _userService.<span class="ems-token-fn">GetByDomainName</span>(identity.Name);
        <span class="ems-token-kw">if</span> (user == <span class="ems-token-kw">null</span> || !user.IsActive) <span class="ems-token-kw">return</span> <span class="ems-token-kw">false</span>;

        httpContext.Items[<span class="ems-token-str">"CurrentUser"</span>] = user;
        <span class="ems-token-kw">return</span> <span class="ems-token-fn">CheckPageAccess</span>(user, httpContext.Request.Url);
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

